data.value: visceromotor, somatosensitive fibers and viscerosensitive fibers. • The trunk of the spinal nerve protrudes from the outside of the vertebral canal through the intervertebral hole (conjugation hole). After a short journey from its exit from the vertebral canal, the spinal nerve breaks down into its branches: Ventral, dorsal, meningeal and white communicative. • The ventral branches of the spinal nerve have in their structure motor and sensory fibers that are distributed to the muscles and skin of the limbs and antero-lateral wall of the trunk. Ventral branches are thicker than dorsal branches and, except for those in the thoracic region, anastomosis and form plexuses. The cervical plexus consists of the ventral branches of the nerves C1 - C4. • The branches of the cervical plexus distribute to the neck. One of its branches, the phrenic nerve, originating in C3-C4, innervates the diaphragm. • The brachial plexus consists of the ventral branches of the C5-C8 nerves and the first thoracic nerve and innervates the scapular belt and the upper limb. • The ventral branches of the thoracic nerves are called intercostal nerves and there are 12. They innervate the muscles and skin in the walls of the chest and abdomen. The lumbar plexus consists of the ventral branches of the first 4 lumbar nerves. Its branches are distributed to the abdominal wall, external genitals and lower limbs. The sacral plexus consists of the ventral branches of L5, S1, S2, S3 and is intended for the pelvic girdle and the lower limb. The shameful plexus contains fibers from the ventral branch of the S4 nerve. It is distributed to the pelvic viscera, external genitalia, and the perineum. • The sacro-coccygeal plexus consists of the ventral branches of the nerves S4-S5 and the coccygeal nerve. It distributes to the muscles of the perineum. • The dorsal branch of the spinal nerve contains, like the ventral branch, both motor and sensory fibers; it distributes to the skin of the back and to the muscles of the spines. • The meningeal branch of the spinal nerve contains sensitive fibers and vasomotor for meninges. • Communicative branch: Through the white one passes the myelin preganglione fiber, originating in the visceromotor neurone from the lateral horn of the marrow, and through the gray one the amielinic postganglion fiber, being the neurone axis from the lateral-vertebral sympathetic vegetative ganglia.

data.value: horn of the marrow impulses are coming from the brain bark, via the cortical and subcortical pyramidal and extrapyramidal beams, and from the spinal ganglion, through the axon of the somatosensory neurone, which connects with somatomotor neurones in the anterior horns either directly (monosinaptic reflex) or through the association neurones (polysynaptic reflex). The anterior root of the spinal nerve also penetrates the axons of the preganglionary (sympathetic) visceromotor neurones in the lateral horns of the marrow (from the visceromotor area), as well as the preganglionary neurones of the sacral parasympathetic. The myelinic Axon of the sympathetic preganglionary neurone penetrates the anterior root of the spinal nerve, which it then leaves through the white communicative branch, reaching its path to a vegetative sympathetic laterovertebral (paravertebral) ganglion. At this level, the synapse is made with a second neurone whose axon, without the myelin sheath, constitutes the postganglion fiber. It either reaches the effector organ (smooth muscle or gland) along a vessel, or reenters through the gray communicating branch into the spinal nerve and, by its path, reaches the effector organ, the hair muscle, sebaceous glands and sweat or to the smooth musculature of blood vessels in the skin and muscles. The pregangliary Axon of the sacred parasympathetic neurone penetrates into the anteritime root that it does not leave, and by this way it reaches a previsceral or intramural ganglion • The posterior (dorsal) root contains 500 000 to 550 000 nerve fibers. On the path of the dorsal root is the spinal ganglion, at which both somatosensitive neurones and viscerosensitive neurones are located. Somatosensitive neurones have a long dendrite that reaches the receptors in the skin (exteroceptors) or deep somatic receptors in the locomotor apparatus (proprioceptors). The Axon of somatosensitive neurones penetrates the posterior root pathway into the marrow, where it behaves in several ways: - It is directly connected to a somatomotor neurone in the anterior horn, forming a monosynaptic reflex arc (beneuronal). - It connects with one or more association neurones and, through their contact, with the somatomotor neurone in the anterior horn of the marrow, thus making a polysynaptic (multi-neuroneal) reflex arc. - Penetrates the gray substance of the marrow (posterior horn), connecting with the second neurone whose axon forms the spinocerebellar (direct and cross) and spinotalamic beams. - It penetrates the white matter of the marrow (posterior horn) into the posterior cord, where it forms the spinobulbar beams Goll and Burdach, which ascend through the posterior cord of the marrow toward the bulb, to meet at this level II neurone, which is based in the nuclei of the Goll and Burdach in the bulb.

data.name: label9.Text
data.value: The spinal nerves connect the marrow with receptors and effectors (somatic and vegetative). There are 31 pairs and they have a metameric disposition. In the cervical region there are 8 cervical nerves (the first protrudes between the occipital bone and the first cervical vertebra), in the thoracic region there are 12 nerves, 5 in the lumbar and sacral region and one in the coccygeal region. The spinal nerves are made up of two roots: One anterior (ventral), motor and one posterior (dorsal), sensory, which shows on its path the spinal ganglia.
